segments.text: Oldest business in Richmond, I believe, has been in business continuously.
I think the oldest one here is a lumber yard.
It wasn't an old lumber company.
That's Joe Clyde Westendorf, right?
Yeah, well, it started out, it was,
Oh, I don't remember now what the old original Wessendorf was here in that lumber business, but his boy, Tony Wessendorf, T.B., they called him, he took over back, somewhere back in 1900 or so.
He was operating it before I started school.
And
Joe was his nephew, wasn't he?
Well, Joe's daddy, that's Joe Clyde's daddy, was his nephew, Tony's nephew.
Then it was Joe Clyde.
And Joe Clyde's granddaddy, who had an insurance business here since way back before I can remember.
And Joe Clyde inherited that from his granddaddy.
Now, the Wessendorffs were some of the original settlers of Richmond, right?
Well, they were pretty well, they were well fixed.
But there was, oh shucks, Bertrand, Winston, Bassett, and so on down the line that had just all kinds of land, cattle, and then farm cutting.
As long as 1919, right after the First World War, cotton, the price of cotton just went way up, you know.
They made a big crop there.
Everybody had lots of money.
But cotton has been the main agricultural crop.
Well...
Then you came along with oil.
There was a mill here that sugarcane.
Across the bridge, you know, where the old Bill Williams Cafe is out there.
That big cafe just a little past it all the way to Sugar Land used to be solid sugarcane.
And the Bertrand Farm sugarcane then.
But when the sugar cane business got to where they couldn't get help, at that time, you could rent convicts from the state.
You had to have a building to keep them in, and bars on the windows, and so forth, and guards.
But you could rent convicts.
I don't have any idea how cheap, but I know they could rent them cheap, because the cane farmers over there used them.
I think cut that out.
Eventually, Sugar Land quit crushing cane.
See, these farmers and the state, the state prison farmers, they didn't raise dogs like sugar cane.
After the cane went out, well, then of course they went to cotton over there.
The prairie farm went to cotton, too.
But I don't know.
It just seemed like the cotton farming, that is, these big farmers, they just gradually went down.
There's more cotton farmers out on the prairie out here in recent years than anywhere.
You're talking about oil.
What is the booths on all of them?
They own most of the oil at Thompson or who does?
No, I wouldn't say.
He said your oil.
The Moore family that I'm talking about, different people here in Richmond had a lot of land.
Now they have sulfur and oil.
And the Goobles is down at Thompson.
That's Burke Goobles and all of them?
That's his folks, his ancestors, his folks.
And Big Creek Oil Field, there's a lot of that.
The A.P.
George family had a lot.
They were big branches and farmers.
Big Creek Oil Field, practically all of it was on Bud Davis' ranch, and he was a brother of Mrs. A.P.
George.
Bud died while she inherited that.
But the big Greek oil field was a sort of a minor operation for a good many years.
They just, oh, here in the last several years, they've drilled wells out there and made lots of wells on that Davis Ranch.
OK, how did Miss Agnes Booth, you know, like, there's, who,
Who's her ancestors?
Is she a George way back?
No, no.
Her husband had the money.
She didn't have it.
She married money.
Mr. Tom Booth had the money.
If our Booth estate is only two areas, then Mrs. August Martin, Tom Booth, and Agnes were married to Tom Booth.
Because I knew, you know, that she
Well, Helen Ann Ragsdale's, you know, her daughter-in-law.
That's her daughter or her daughter-in-law?
It's her daughter.
Daughter, that's right.
I guess it would be.
Well, I know Helen Ann's been married a few times.
But anyway, like, she, you know, she gets a lot of that money from those estates, you know, her un-gas amount that she was receiving.
I couldn't believe it.
But speaking about oil, Mr. Blaze, have you worked in the fields out here much?
Thompson and Big Creek.
Yeah, I worked at Thompson, Big Creek, Blue Ridge, and very little at Damon.
In fact, I was real well just about any of them up and down the coast.
That was when they had the Wooden Derricks and the R.M.N., right?
That's when I started to have Wooden Derricks.
Wooden derrick was pretty handy on cold nights.
Cold nights in that derrick.
Wooden derrick legs, all of that.
Come out about so far each way from the corner of the derrick, you could back up in there and get out of that cold wind.
Have you always been in the oil field?
Since you've been here in Richmond?
Well...
I mean, most of the time.
Practically most of the time.
I pulled around both filling stations once and got out for a while.
The only way I've ever been able to make a living, though, off of you.
Yeah.
He liked it, that's the way it goes.
Yeah, I know, sir.
I started rough-necking at that big creek.
In fact, the first job I ever had was to find a boiler.
Not a boiler, an A-boiler.
A small one, at that.
You worked the boiler?
You were, well, actually a motorman, right?
Huh?
Farmer.
Farmer?
Oh.
Well, there was an old man by the name of Rich.
He promoted money to the River Wildcat down there across the creek from Big Creek off me.
And he got down, oh, about 2,500 feet and had some six-inch casings set and run out of money.
And he hired me to drive while he was rigged.
So I was out there laying around watching that rig.
Wasn't there a way for anybody to get in there and get him?
There ain't anyone that's walked.
So he got a little more money together.
The driller come out there with a dead man and two roughnecks.
Told me he was a father and mother of a mother's wife.
He said, Father Boyle, you had your driver watching you, the farmer.
With a little instruction from some of these roughnecks, I learned what to do to get some steam up.
So I was a farmer.
Fired with oil.
Yeah, that's where I started.
And then after he run out of money, then again, then I went to work in the Gulf out there, roughly.
Gulf oil company?
Mm-hmm.
Who owns most of the wells down there?
Isn't it Humboldt?
Or Walexone?
In Big Creek?
Well, in Thompson and Big Creek.
Well, in Big Creek, the Gulf Company got practically everything out there.
Thompson and Gulf and Humboldt.
How about Orchard, Joe?
How about Orchard?
Well, Gulf got the biggest part of that.
Sulphur, too?
Well, the...
No, what's the name of that sulfur company?
The plant now is shut down.
They're getting all that sulfur out there in West Texas now.
But, oh, shucks, what's the name of that sulfur company?
Duval.
Duval, yeah.
When did they start, you know, drilling down here at Thompson?
Thompson, they discovered, well, Thompson came in in 1932.
But Big Creek, let's see, I believe in 1922, they moved a little steam rig in there, which, of course, at that time, this was a pretty good-sized drilling rig.
But they drilled a well there on top of the dome, made a well that was 650 feet.
It never was a whole lot of producer, but then they had to have oil to fire boil it with.
And it amounted to a good bit.
They pumped it there for a long time, the gasoline engine.
There.
Oh, they just jumped here and there and young of them.
They make a well of caged linen, make a dry hole, put a rug in it.
But they have gotten out here in the last, oh, eight, nine years or so, and got off around 80.
They don't make a lot of wells.
They're all pumping wells, but they're old.
On that T.W.
Davis lease, there must be isolated wells.
There has been over 200 wells drilled on it, but they're not all produced.
They've got a good bit of production there on those pumping wells.
Thompson Field.
The golf company had that whole thing back in that leased up, back in that bottom.
And they didn't think enough of it to drill a wildcat.
So they gave Cullen West half interest in the whole work down there to drill a wildcat.
And they went back in there.
They had to cut trees down, build corduroy roads.
And about the only way you could get in there was on a cat or horseback.
But they made a well on the first hole, and they made a well there.
And then the Covington West finally sold their half inches to the Humble Company.
That's the way the Humble Company got in there.
It wasn't Thompson, that was almost all black, right?
What?
Blacks, Negroes, right?
Wasn't Thompson a lot of Negroes down there?
Oh, yeah, they were.
There were a lot of people on the ranch area and big places down there.
Before that oil field came in, there was, oh, sure, the majority of the people were Negroes.
However, there was one old nugget down there, old Y.U.
Jones, that was worth a world of money.
Y.U.
Jones, is he still alive?
No.
Because I know there's a Y.U.
Jones that I remember.
That I know now.
Okay, that's Y.U.
Jones that works it.
Because I see him.
But Y.U.
Jones, I don't think he ever got any money out of the oil business except at least money.
He was...
were practically cattlemen and nothing else.
Can we go back to agriculture?
Yes, ma'am.
In the early 1930s, they began to plant rice here.
And they had a hard time making a go of it.
They had a good year, fine, but, you know, some years weren't so good because they depended on manual labor.
And I know that

they really had a rough time of it the wives worked in stores and they did lots of things to help out to make things go then of course when it became mechanical it became a major agricultural activity in our county and they made a lot of money but like rice and let's see cotton and sugarcane but that's the only three things that they grow they don't grow any soybeans or
They've never made a go with soybeans or corn?
Well, they just... Well, a little maize, right?
Corn and maize for their own use, primarily.
They're rarely going to maize and soybeans now.
Right, but they do.
Primarily, your farmer planted cotton for his income and grains for his own use and hay for himself for his stock.
Okay, going back to the Negroes, most of them around here were
were former, well, descendants of former slaves, right?
And that's how they got most of their land, like the ones over here on Thompson Highway?
The biggest part of them back in the day was a tenant farm.
The farming for white folks, that's the way they got their crops in.
But down around Thompson, it's
There's really been more cattle propagation down there than back years ago.
Old Boss Slavin, Judy Hampton.
Been to Booth, of course, on back land back in there.
Yeah, the old Herzog plantation down there, too.
The old Herzog place down there, I think at times had been farmed a little back in there.
But it's up this side of Thompson
That's where we lived in 1913.
I was a baby.
Have y'all lived in, I mean, y'all, where all have y'all lived, you know, like since y'all got married?
Have y'all lived in Richmond?
Richmond, Rosenberg for a little, for about a year, not a year, not quite a year.
Just about a year.
We've lived here ever since.
44 years in Richmond.
Not in this house, right?
Lived in it 38.
Some years.
Let's see, 1941, 33 years last September.
And what all have you done?
I mean, places like, as your career, like if you just started, did you just start working at Gulf Coast in 58 on tax assessment?
No.
I started out with Houston Lighting and Power Company after I finished high school.
Then I married.
And we had stopped, and we had three children.
And then I went to work in the courthouse, the tax collector.
And then when the war came along, I worked.
I was chief clerk of the draft board for five years.
And then after the war was over, but before the end of the draft office, I quit and went back to the tax collector's office.
Okay, what changes did you notice, like, during the war when, like, most of the men were away?

Did this community become more dependent on the, for instance, like the women, did they take over the stores and most of the businesses, or did, you know, like, was it just most of the young men that went?
Most of the young men.
Mostly young men.
We didn't have
Well, of course, to begin with, your age limit was 38, but you didn't draft them up to 38.
They could volunteer, but 26 was about as high as we drafted, unless they had had deferments for some reason or other which put them past that age.
No, there were enough men here to run things, and then...
Of course, a lot of people went to Houston to work because of, well, they made parts for ships and boilers for ships, and I don't know what all, in Houston during the war.
And a lot of people, that's when they began commuting.
But Richmond started to grow right after the war, right?
Yes, the whole area started to grow.
Okay.
I wouldn't say right after, because for a little while, it was hard to get materials.
But as soon as things became available, yes, it began to grow.
So I guess that covers everything.
You have anything else to say or think of?
Well, we've seen lots of changes.
paved streets when they used to be so muddy, you'd get bogged down in Rosenberg, so sandy you'd get stuck in the sand over here in Spots, and air conditioning and all these things, and better cars.
We've seen a lot of things change.
When they got natural gas in here, they got running water, hot water, and you see Richmond
Talk about these streets, Richmond sitting on Sandy, this main part of town, where there's nothing but sand.
And the streets, when it was dry, when the sand blew and the buggy wheels kind of bogged up in that sand,
So they went down on the river and dug up a bunch of clay and all, and then put clay on the streets to get out of the sand.
Well, then when it rained, it got snow and muddy.
So then they bought gravel and had it shipped in here and graveled the streets with big old rocks, a lot of it, like this.
And then they'd get graveled up over in Colorado County.
And finally, then, to get away from the rocks were the blacktop streets.
That's where we are now.
We have a very active library here now, a museum, I mean.
And that little house between the bridges down here, you know, your east and westbound bridges?
Yes, ma'am.
The handworks?
That little antique shop?
Well, it's the handworks.
It's for arts and crafts.
and go down and take courses in various arts and crafts and some of them old.
That was Carrie Nation's daughter's home.
Carrie Nation.
Carrie Nation's the woman with the axe that went around breaking up the saloons.
Yeah, yeah.
Remember?
That's her.
During Prohibition.
Right.
Was she from here?
The daughter lived here in that house, and Carrie Nation spent much of her time with her in that house.
Where did she go around breaking?
Wherever there was a saloon.
Was it here in Texas she broke up the saloon?
Not just Fort Bend County or Richmond, but she went up north or anywhere and chopped up the board with a hatchet.
She was a character.
Talking about prohibition, was there a lot of bootlegging and bathtub liquor and all that, bathtub gin that went on right here?
Joe can tell you more about that than I.
There wasn't much whiskey cooking in this county as there was anywhere else in Texas, I imagine.
I used to think the only way a farmer could live on a booth estate and farm was to be able to cook good whiskey.
Yeah, I had a filling station out here where Melvin Lindeman's garage is.
Yes, sir.
And that catacomb across the street over there was another filling station.
where that 66 is now, the Davis Park?
Davis Park.
Where the Davis Park on that corner.
Yes, sir.
In fact, the driveway of the filling station was built up, was blocked up where that water could run through there, you know.
And I had a sort of a shop there in the back of the station back in,
And then no mechanic in it or anything.
I just kept it more or less for storage or what have you.
But there was room enough to get four-file cars in there.
I went out there to open up one morning, and there's Italians over there in the driveway over at the other station.
They hadn't opened up.
These guys had a modulated Ford truck, stake bed on it, tarp on it.
Well, I knew who it was.
Running whiskey, bringing whiskey from down there in the bottom going to Houston.
And they wanted to, they traded over there.
They never did trade with me.
And old Bert Ansel was running that station.
He come down in the morning and wanted to store that truck, and he didn't have any place for him to put it.
So they come over, come over to see me and want to know if I had room in that storage out here.
I had room in that storage.
Well, they might leave it a day, might leave it two or three days.
So...
They took off.
They drove a truck in there and took off.
I knew they had a load of whiskey.
I got up and looked under the tarp and see what size kegs they had.
Went down.
My brother-in-law was running a meat market down there.
I went down there and asked him if he had a place to put some whiskey.
when he just got a bunch of, filled his barn up with cotton seed hulls over there.
And so we went down.
It so happened there wasn't very many new kegs in town.
And we got ahold of three kegs, took them out there and filled them up with water and put them on that truck.
Took three of them kegs of whiskey off the floor of that cedar house.
Come back here at noon, I saw them dollar and a half store in the truck.
You know, I didn't know about that.
I'm learning things.
Some of their customers, some of their customers somewhere down the line, I imagine, was a little unhappy.
I imagine so.
